# Story

Odinn was born in a humble village in the far south of Narnlund. He was born with a special kind of soul‚Äîone double-kissed by the divine. He was a Sparkbearer‚Äîa soul with a divine spark which Odinn was destined to bear. The spark granted him immense strength and longevity, along with an unalterable destiny. Each Sparkbearer receives a trial unique to them. Odinn got his in his sixteenth year, when the primordial dragon Fafnir appeared in a vision and spoke the words that would shape his future: *Your trial: "Live an honorable life, and die an honorable death."* From that moment, the path of his life was set in stone.

As a member of the giant race, the Narn, Odinn's honor was already bound to the strict codes of his people. To lead with strength and to die defending one's name‚Äîthese were the highest virtues. He became a king early in his life, and though he possessed great might, he never sought glory or conquest. He was a warrior, yes, but not for pride. He led with caution, with wisdom, and with a fierce desire to bring his people home from every battle. Each choice he made, each war he waged, was guided by his trial.

With his realm prosperous and his people content, Odinn prepared for the final stage of his trial. A peaceful death would not suffice. Following Narn tradition, he issued a challenge: any warrior who could defeat him in single combat would claim his collected treasures‚Äîand unknowingly complete his divine trial.

Decades passed with the challenge open. Many answered the challenge. None succeeded. Some challengers died. Most left humbled. And the weight of an unfinished trial continued to press upon the king's broad shoulders.

